  "summary": "Inspector Claddock enters the manor through the back door and encounters Lucy, who is making peach pies, and Brian, who is standing by the pantry. Claddock asks for Mr. Sedgwick, and Brian directs him to the study. Before proceeding, Claddock confronts Lucy regarding a bag of envelopes containing forged postmarks, which he believes she placed in the boiler room for the children to find, but Lucy expresses confusion.\n\nIn the study, Claddock questions Sedgwick about his whereabouts on Friday, December 20th, the day of the murder. Sedgwick initially claims he was in Ibiza, describing a routine of painting, sketching, and visiting cafes. He attempts to use Emma to corroborate his claim that he arrived in Britain on the Saturday before Christmas, but Claddock reveals that records show Sedgwick actually arrived on the evening of December 19th.\n\nAfter Emma leaves the room to allow for a private conversation, Sedgwick admits he lied. He confesses that he arrived in London on the 19th with a beautiful woman he met on a plane, using the alias \"John Brown\" at the Kingsway Hotel. Regarding the 20th, Sedgwick claims he spent the morning with a hangover, visited the National Gallery in the afternoon, watched a movie, and visited various entertainment spots, including a place called \"Jumping Frog,\" with the woman. He states he became heavily intoxicated and does not remember much until the next day, when he traveled to Lutterworth, pretending he had just landed at Heathrow to avoid worrying Emma.",
